 id=3D"main-content" class=3D"awsui-util-container"><div id=3D"main-col-bod=
y"><awsdocs-language-banner data-service=3D"$ctrl.pageService"></awsdocs-la=
nguage-banner><h1 class=3D"topictitle" id=3D"bp-adjacency-graphs">Best prac=
tices for managing many-to-many
      relationships in DynamoDB tables</h1><div class=3D"awsdocs-page-heade=
r-container"><awsdocs-page-header></awsdocs-page-header><awsdocs-filter-sel=
ector id=3D"awsdocs-filter-selector"></awsdocs-filter-selector></div><p>Adj=
acency lists are a design pattern that is useful for modeling many-to-many =
relationships
    in Amazon DynamoDB. More generally, they provide a way to represent gra=
ph data (nodes and edges) in
    DynamoDB.</p>
    <h2 id=3D"bp-adjacency-lists">Adjacency list design pattern</h2>
    <p>When different entities of an application have a many-to-many relati=
onship between them,
      the relationship can be modeled as an adjacency list. In this pattern=
, all top-level entities
      (synonymous to nodes in the graph model) are represented using the pa=
rtition key. Any
      relationships with other entities (edges in a graph) are represented =
as an item within the
      partition by setting the value of the sort key to the target entity I=
D (target node).</p>
    <p>The advantages of this pattern include minimal data duplication and =
simplified query
      patterns to find all entities (nodes) related to a target entity (hav=
ing an edge to a target
      node).</p>
    <p>A real-world example where this pattern has been useful is an invoic=
ing system where
      invoices contain multiple bills. One bill can belong in multiple invo=
ices. The partition key
      in this example is either an <code class=3D"code">InvoiceID</code> or=
 a <code class=3D"code">BillID</code>.
        <code class=3D"code">BillID</code> partitions have all attributes s=
pecific to bills. <code class=3D"code">InvoiceID</code>
      partitions have an item storing invoice-specific attributes, and an i=
tem for each
        <code class=3D"code">BillID</code> that rolls up to the invoice.</p=
>
    <p>The schema looks like the following.</p>
    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/AdjacencyLists_01.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"Table schema for billing adjacency-list exam=
ple." style=3D"max-width:100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
    <p>Using the preceding schema, you can see that all bills for an invoic=
e can be queried using
      the primary key on the table. To look up all invoices that contain a =
part of a bill, create a
      global secondary index on the table's sort key. </p>
    <p>The projections for the global secondary index look like the followi=
ng.</p>
    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/AdjacencyLists_02.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"GSI projection for billing adjacency-list ex=
ample." style=3D"max-width:100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
  =20
    <h2 id=3D"bp-graph-pattern">Materialized graph pattern</h2>
    <p>Many applications are built around understanding rankings across pee=
rs, common
      relationships between entities, neighbor entity state, and other type=
s of graph style
      workflows. For these types of applications, consider the following sc=
hema design
      pattern.</p>
    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/1513869910203-418.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"Graph example number 1." style=3D"max-width:=
100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/1513852802235-256.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"Graph example number 2." style=3D"max-width:=
100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/1513852905360-671.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"Graph example number 3." style=3D"max-width:=
100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
    <p>The preceding schema shows a graph data structure that is defined by=
 a set of data
      partitions containing the items that define the edges and nodes of th=
e graph. Edge items
      contain a <code class=3D"code">Target</code> and a <code class=3D"cod=
e">Type</code> attribute. These attributes are used as
      part of a composite key name "TypeTarget" to identify the item in a p=
artition in the primary
      table or in a second global secondary index.</p>
    <p>The first global secondary index is built on the <code class=3D"code=
">Data</code> attribute. This
      attribute uses global secondary index-overloading as described earlie=
r to index several
      different attribute types, namely <code class=3D"code">Dates</code>, =
<code class=3D"code">Names</code>, <code class=3D"code">Places</code>,
      and <code class=3D"code">Skills</code>. Here, one global secondary in=
dex is effectively indexing four
      different attributes.</p>
    <p>As you insert items into the table, you can use an intelligent shard=
ing strategy to
      distribute item sets with large aggregations (birthdate, skill) acros=
s as many logical
      partitions on the global secondary indexes as are needed to avoid hot=
 read/write
      problems.</p>
    <p>The result of this combination of design patterns is a solid datasto=
re for highly
      efficient real-time graph workflows. These workflows can provide high=
-performance neighbor
      entity state and edge aggregation queries for recommendation engines,=
 social-networking
      applications, node rankings, subtree aggregations, and other common g=
raph use cases.</p>
    <p>If your use case isn't sensitive to real-time data consistency, you =
can use a scheduled
      Amazon EMR process to populate edges with relevant graph summary aggr=
egations for your workflows.
      If your application doesn't need to know immediately when an edge is =
added to the graph, you
      can use a scheduled process to aggregate results.</p>
    <p>To maintain some level of consistency, the design could include Amaz=
on DynamoDB Streams and
      AWS Lambda to process edge updates. It could also use an Amazon EMR j=
ob to validate results on a
      regular interval. This approach is illustrated by the following diagr=
am. It is commonly used
      in social networking applications, where the cost of a real-time quer=
y is high and the need to
      immediately know individual user updates is low.</p>

    <div class=3D"mediaobject">
      =20
        <img src=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/amazondynamodb/lates=
t/developerguide/images/1513856345673-336.png" class=3D"aws-docs-img-whiteB=
g aws-docs-img-padding" alt=3D"Diagram illustrating graph workflow." style=
=3D"max-width:100%">
      =20
      =20
    </div>
    <p>IT service-management (ITSM) and security applications generally nee=
d to respond in real
      time to entity state changes composed of complex edge aggregations. S=
uch applications need a
      system that can support real-time multiple node aggregations of secon=
d- and third-level
      relationships, or complex edge traversals. If your use case requires =
these types of real-time
      graph query workflows, we recommend that you consider using <a href=
=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/">Amazon
        Neptune</a> to manage these workflows.</p>
    <div class=3D"awsdocs-note"><div class=3D"awsdocs-note-title"><awsui-ic=
on name=3D"status-info" variant=3D"link"></awsui-icon><h6>Note</h6></div><d=
iv class=3D"awsdocs-note-text"><p>If you need to query highly connected dat=
asets or execute queries that need to traverse
        multiple nodes (also known as multi-hop queries) with millisecond l=
atency, you should
        consider using <a href=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/lates=
t/userguide/">Amazon Neptune</a>. Amazon Neptune is a
        purpose-built, high-performance graph database engine optimized for=
 storing billions of
        relationships and querying the graph with millisecond latency.</p><=
/div></div>
